Raf Simons to Step Down at Christian Dior 
 
Raf Simons is stepping down as creative director of Christian Dior, LVMH announced this morning.
“It is after careful and long consideration that I have decided to leave my position as creative director of Christian Dior’s women’s collection,” Simons said in a statement. “It is a decision based entirely and equally on my desire to focus ... on other interests in my life, including my own brand, and the passions that drive me outside my work. Christian Dior is an extraordinary company, and it has been an immense privilege to write a few pages of this magnificent book. ... heartfelt, and inspired management will also remain as one of the most important experiences of my professional career.”
Simons joined Dior in early 2012, presenting his first couture collection for the storied Paris house in July of that year. Azzedine Alaïa, ... the previous seven years at Jil Sander while simultaneously running his own menswear label out of Antwerp, stepped in at Dior more than a year after John Galliano was dismissed from the house in the wake of Galliano’s anti-Semitic remarks. Simons became the sixth designer to officially hold the reins after Dior himself, Yves Saint Laurent, Marc Bohan, Gianfranco Ferré, and Galliano.
His first effort was a triumph. Respectful yet bold, it demonstrated his keen understanding of such Dior codes as the iconic Bar jacket, coupled with a modern sense of irreverence, as symbolized in the gowns he draped from silks based on his friend Sterling Ruby’s paintings. The collection yielded a sensitive documentary, Dior and I, showcasing the challenges Simons surmounted as a newcomer in the house’s couture ateliers. Dior is one of fashion’s most prestigious posts; Belgian outsider though he may be, Simons’s debut signaled he was more than up to the task.

He’s taken Dior’s pre-season collections everywhere from Pierre Cardin’s famous Palais Bulles in the South of France to a sumo wrestling arena in ... ride from Manhattan to the Brooklyn Navy Yard for the label’s Resort 2015 show was unforgettable, with the clients’ latest Dior whipping in the East River wind.
When discussing his work for the house, Simons has often spoken about time—“a nostaglia ... are second to none.
Simons’s abrupt departure will undoubtedly spark renewed talks about the difficulties of overseeing a brand of Dior’s size and the almost inhuman demands of the current fashion cycle. Simons was responsible for six Dior collections a year; his Spring 2016 show was his last.
